---
import DocsNav from '../../components/DocsNav.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import SiteNav from '../../components/SiteNav.astro';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Memory and learning · neondeck"
  description="How Neondeck stores durable memory, curates current guidance, and keeps active sessions stable."
>
  <div class="site-shell">
    <SiteNav />
    <main class="container docs-layout">
      <DocsNav />
      <article class="docs-prose">
        <h1>Memory and learning</h1>
        <p>
          Neondeck memory is a small current working set of durable guidance. It
          is not a transcript archive and it is not an evidence graph. Chat
          history, watch state, workflow summaries, and repo facts stay in their
          own stores; memory keeps the guidance Neon should carry into future
          sessions.
        </p>

        <h2>Scopes</h2>
        <p>New memory writes use three active learning scopes.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><code>user</code>: durable user preferences and expectations.</li>
          <li>
            <code>local</code>: machine, tool, provider, CLI, and workflow facts
            that are not tied to one repository.
          </li>
          <li>
            <code>project</code>: repo, product, team, verification, and deploy
            conventions.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Older <code>session</code> and <code>watch</code> memories may still be
          readable for compatibility, but new learning writes do not create them.
          Session state belongs in Flue transcripts plus Neondeck session summaries.
          Watch state belongs in watch tables, watermarks, notifications, and workflow
          summaries.
        </p>

        <h2>Active and archived</h2>
        <p>
          Memory rows have <code>active</code> or <code>archived</code> status. Active
          rows can load into new session prompt snapshots. Archived rows stay available
          for history and audit, but they do not shape new prompts.
        </p>
        <p>
          Rewrites and merges replace old guidance with clearer current
          guidance. Archiving is preferred over physical deletion so the audit
          trail can explain what changed.
        </p>

        <h2>Actions</h2>
        <p>
          Neon changes memory through typed Valibot-backed actions:
          <code>neondeck_memory_learn</code>,
          <code>neondeck_memory_rewrite</code>,
          <code>neondeck_memory_merge</code>,
          <code>neondeck_memory_archive</code>,
          <code>neondeck_memory_candidate_*</code>, and
          <code>neondeck_memory_curate</code>. These actions write audit events
          with before and after snapshots.
        </p>

        <h2>Curation</h2>
        <p>
          Memory curation keeps the active working set bounded. Configure it in
          runtime-home <code>config.json</code>.
        </p>
        <pre><code>&#123;
  "learning": &#123;
    "memoryCurationEnabled": true,
    "memoryCurationMode": "review",
    "memoryCurationTurnInterval": 200,
    "memoryMaxActiveItems": 200
  &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
        <p>
          <code>off</code> disables automatic curation. <code>review</code>
          creates candidates for approval. <code>auto</code> may apply safe, audited
          typed actions; the current foundation only auto-applies bounded archive
          cleanup for overflow memories.
        </p>

        <h2>Audit history</h2>
        <p>
          <code>data/neondeck.db</code> stores <code>memories</code>,
          <code>memory_events</code>, <code>learning_events</code>,
          <code>learning_reviews</code>, and <code>learning_candidates</code>.
          Suspicious or secret-like writes are rejected and audited without
          becoming active prompt-loadable memory.
        </p>

        <h2>Session stability</h2>
        <p>
          Memory writes take effect in durable state immediately, but active
          display-assistant sessions are not silently rewritten. New or changed
          memory marks relevant sessions stale. Start a new session, or use a
          future explicit context-refresh flow, to load the new prompt snapshot.
        </p>

        <h2>Model role</h2>
        <p>
          <code>models.selfImprovement</code> and
          <code>models.selfImprovementThinkingLevel</code> reserve a model role for
          bounded learning reviews and future reflection workflows. The current foundation
          uses deterministic memory actions and curation. If omitted, Neondeck falls
          back through
          <code>FLUE_SELF_IMPROVEMENT_MODEL</code>, the utility model,
          <code>FLUE_UTILITY_MODEL</code>, the display assistant model,
          <code>FLUE_AGENT_MODEL</code>, and then the built-in default.
        </p>
      </article>
    </main>
    <SiteFooter />
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
